  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><h4>Awareness — Life at VUS</h4><p style="font-size:14px;">Outperforms on both reach (22.89% vs. 16.84% of posts) and engagement (26.26%), yet generates only 0.76% of link clicks — the exact signature of a healthy awareness pillar. The issue: it's <b>significantly under-invested</b> relative to its actual performance.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Consideration — VUS Culture &amp; Values</h4><p style="font-size:14px;">Drives 26.49% of link clicks from just 15.82% of posts — a clear outperformance. When audiences see culture content, they get curious and want to learn more — a clear consideration-intent signal.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Conversion — Teach at VUS</h4><p style="font-size:14px;">Accounts for 51.87% of link clicks — correctly playing the CTA/conversion role. The risk: it occupies nearly a third of the entire content feed, which risks making the Page read as a job board rather than an appealing brand.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Bottleneck — Vietnam &amp; Relocation</h4><p style="font-size:14px;">Underperforms on <b>every</b> metric: reach -49%, engagement -74%, link clicks -96% relative to its post share. This can't be explained away by "niche audience" alone — it points to a real content/targeting problem.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">"Other" isn't a mis-categorization — it's a content format/tone that hasn't been formally recognized yet. This will be decoded in Section 05.</div>
</section>

